The original Bug Heroes was so much better. This game has no semblance of balance. Either you'll breeze through the round with barely any challenge whatsoever, or you'll be buried under endless waves of ridiculously powerful enemies with no hope of completing the round regardless of what you do. I originally rage uninstalled after continuous crashes during long games. Then I decided I liked the game enough to try and help identify the crashing issues (which seems to be fairly common based on other reviews).  I reinstalled, turned all the graphics down, turned off sound/music, and turned vibration off.  The graphics still look great and I haven't had any crashes since - it's awesome.  I don't know exactly which setting was causing the problems but my money is on the vibration. If you have had crashing problems in the past I'd recommend giving it another try with all these options turned off.  Anyway, the game itself is great. There is a ton of single player content, which is both challenging, diverse, and fun.  I haven't tried multiplayer but have no expectations. I think it would be fun to try and get real life friends to play online together, but it is not critical and certainly you get your money's worth from single player.

The game is actually more complex than it seems at first. As well as having different stats and abilities, the various bug heroes have different upgrades during a game  (weapon, armor and 2 equipment slots), which makes each suited to certain roles (eg tanking v dps v crowd control, base defence v roaming etc). Add to this the variety of base upgrades (turrets, shields, troop generators) and you have a nice range of tactical options to play with. The IAPs are really optional as you can earn crystals (and new heroes) just by playing the game; the pricing is also very reasonable if you do want to spend a bit. The single player mode is very well developed, but there is also multi player for those who want it.

I absolutely love how this MOBA is completely tailored to mobile devices... From the controls down to the one versus one game play, with no need to form groups or have to fill teams with bots, to allow you to get in multiplayer games quicker. The campaign is also fun to play and objectives can be interesting. There is also a tremendous amount of depth to the character progression system, as well as the way characters equip themselves and unlock and upgrade skills during combat. The IAPs are completely avoidable, but for those of you that get into the game, there are several banner gems you can purchase that will increase how quickly you can level and unlock new content.
